ptype gid - uint 
x/10i $pc -> shows next 10 instructions
disas (disassemble)


(gdb) bt              # backtrace
(gdb) bt full         # with locals/args
(gdb) frame 0         # select a frame
(gdb) info frame      # frame details (sp, saved regs, etc.)

Inspect variables (locals, args, globals)

See locals & args in current frame:

(gdb) info locals
(gdb) info args


Print / pretty print / type:

(gdb) p var
(gdb) p/x var         # hex
(gdb) p/d var         # signed decimal
(gdb) p/u var         # unsigned
(gdb) p/t var         # binary
(gdb) ptype var       # type info


Pointers & memory:

(gdb) p &var
(gdb) x/16xb &var     # examine 16 bytes at &var
(gdb) x/10i $pc       # show next 10 instructions

Change variables (force behavior)

Direct assignment (same type):

(gdb) set var counter = 42
(gdb) set var buf[0] = 'A'


Type-casted write (structs/packed memory):

(gdb) set {int}0x7fffffffe2c0 = 1337
(gdb) set {char[5]}buf = "PWN\0"


Force function to return a value from current frame:

(gdb) return 0         # sets return value and unwinds
(gdb) finish           # run until current function returns (shows retval)


Call a function to mutate state:

(gdb) call reset_state()

Make the next step do what you want

Source-level stepping:

(gdb) next        # step over (don’t enter calls)
(gdb) step        # step into
(gdb) finish      # run to end of current function
(gdb) until 123   # run until reaching source line 123
(gdb) advance func_name  # run until next time PC reaches func entry


Instruction-level precision:

(gdb) layout asm              # TUI asm view (optional)
(gdb) set disassemble-next-line on
(gdb) disassemble /r $pc,$pc+32   # see bytes & next instructions
(gdb) stepi                    # single instruction
(gdb) nexti                    # next instruction, skip over calls


Rewrite the future:

(gdb) set $pc = 0x401234   # jump execution to any address (careful)
(gdb) jump *0x401234       # same idea; stops before executing there

Watchpoints (follow variable changes live)

Data watch:

(gdb) watch var         # stop when var is written
(gdb) rwatch var        # stop when var is read
(gdb) awatch var        # stop on read or write


Raw address watch (struct field, pointer target):

(gdb) watch -location *ptr
(gdb) watch -location ((struct S*)0x...)->field

Reverse for “what just changed this?” 

Lightweight recording:

(gdb) record
(gdb) reverse-stepi
(gdb) reverse-next
(gdb) reverse-continue


(Use record stop to end. Recording costs performance/memory but is gold for backtracking writes.)

Multithreading (don’t get fooled)

Focus and lock scheduling:

(gdb) info threads
(gdb) thread 3
(gdb) set scheduler-locking on   # only current thread runs when stepping


Break on thread creation:

(gdb) set stop-on-solib-events 1
(gdb) set stop-on-thread-events 1

Fork/exec boundaries (keep control across execve)
(gdb) set follow-fork-mode child
(gdb) set detach-on-fork off
(gdb) catch exec        # stop when exec occurs
(gdb) catch syscall execve